<ul id="commtree_65242907"><li id="tree_65242965" class="comment full contain"><span class="ind"></span>
<div id="comment_status_65242965" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_65242965" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_65242965" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a rel="nofollow" id="comment_link_65242965" name="comment_link_65242965" href="//news.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23639749&amp;cid=65242965" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(65242965)" >Re:Cheap Labour is Fundamentally a Crutch</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_65242965" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 65242965); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>5</a>, Interesting)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~drinkypoo">drinkypoo</a>  <span class="uid"><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~drinkypoo">( 153816 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_65242965">		 &lt;<a href="mailto:drink%40hyperlogos.org">drink@hyperlogos.org</a>&gt;
		on Tuesday March 18, 2025 @02:42PM (<span class="ind"></span><a rel="nofollow" href="//news.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23639749&amp;cid=65242965">#65242965</a>)
		<small><a href="http://hyperlogos.org/" title="http://hyperlogos.org/" class="user_homepage_display">Homepage</a>
<a href="//slashdot.org/~drinkypoo/journal/" title="Sunday September 17, 2023 @09:53AM" class="user_journal_display">Journal</a> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_65242965"><p><div class="quote"><p>What is the obsession people have with paying burger flippers more? They are already going past the affordability range of their target customer base.</p></div><p>That's not because of wages, it's because of profits. Due to volume and efficient design, labor is a very small portion of the cost of producing fast food. They literally design fast food "restaurants" around efficiency concepts like <em>reducing the number of steps a worker has to take.</em> I worked in one of the first new "central grill" Wendy's stores as a teenager. I was the fry guy and I did almost all of the walking, because that person did most of the fetching tasks so that nobody else had to, <em>because they have time.</em> They have the bare minimum staff in order to operate the facility. You queue up some fries on the rack under the warmer, then you go fetch the meat and load it into the cooler, or you go get some fries and put them on the slacking rack, or you go get a can of chili base and open it...</p><p>Most fast food restaurants raised their prices during the peak of the Covid-19 PHE by twice as much as their costs increased <em>or more.</em> Most of them tried to maintain them after that and found that customers were opting out of their artificially high prices, so they have since either reduced prices across the board or created limited lower-cost menus of things they know they can sling quickly and cheaply.</p><p>TL;DR: If you think increasing burger flippers' wages to a living wage (why are you obsessed with them getting paid less than they can live on?) will significantly increase fast food prices, you know nothing about fast food pricing.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_65242965">
